{"id":"1912.05197","submitter":"Shivani Goel Ms","authors":"Balaji Ramamurthy, Ravindra Bapat and Shivani Goel","title":"Distance matrices perturbed by a Laplacian","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO math.FA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Let $T$ be a tree with $n$ vertices. To each edge of $T$, we assign a weight\nwhich is a positive definite matrix of some fixed order, say, $s$. Let $D_{ij}$\ndenote the sum of all the weights lying in the path connecting the vertices $i$\nand $j$ of $T$. We now say that $D_{ij}$ is the distance between $i$ and $j$.\nDefine $D:=[D_{ij}]$, where $D_{ii}$ is the $s \\times s$ null matrix and for $i\n\\neq j$, $D_{ij}$ is the distance between $i$ and $j$. Let $G$ be an arbitrary\nconnected weighted graph with $n$ vertices, where each weight is a positive\ndefinite matrix of order $s$. If $i$ and $j$ are adjacent, then define\n$L_{ij}:=-W_{ij}^{-1}$, where $W_{ij}$ is the weight of the edge $(i,j)$.\nDefine $L_{ii}:=\\sum_{i \\neq j,j=1}^{n}W_{ij}^{-1}$. The Laplacian of $G$ is\nnow the $ns \\times ns$ block matrix $L:=[L_{ij}]$. In this paper, we first note\nthat $D^{-1}-L$ is always non-singular and then we prove that $D$ and its\nperturbation $(D^{-1}-L)^{-1}$ have many interesting properties in common.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 11 Dec 2019 09:29:23 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-12-12"}
